    "James W. Knox": ", we continue with, And he taught them many things by parables. There had been no parables up to this time. What had been open now becomes private. And when he was alone, they that were about him with the twelve asked of him the parable. And he said unto them, Unto you (not His family, not the nation, but the disciples who believed) it is given to know the mystery of the kingdom of God: but unto them that are without (His earthly family, His earthly nation) all these things are done in parables: That seeing they may see (physical) and not perceive (spiritual) and hearing they may hear (physical) and not understand; (spiritual) lest at any time they should be converted, and their sins should be forgiven them (vv. 10-12). So we see early in Mark that Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` drew the line on those within the nation who rejected the revelation of Him as their Messiah. There would have been none sick in Israel had they been true to Jehovah. Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` healed their sick. There would have been none possessed of devils had they kept the holy law. Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` cast out their devils. He showed Himself to be the all-powerful God come in the flesh who would graciously cleanse them. They refused Him. As a result, truth previously revealed was withdrawn from them. This is no Calvinist decree of damnation but the darkness that ensues when light is scorned. [v_Mat_12_46] [v_Mat_12_47] [v_Mat_12_48] [v_Mat_12_49] [v_Mat_12_50] Watch the similar transition in Matthew 12:46-\n2. They are being judged ON EARTH (\n2. In chapters 2-3 of Revelation we read of the activity of the local churches.\n2. The Crown of Life This crown will be given those who loved the Lord Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Christ enough to deny temptation. Blessed is the man that endureth temptation: for when he is tried, he shall receive the crown of life, [v_Jas_1_12] which the Lord hath promised to them that love him (James 1:12). Although this is often called the martyr\u2019s crown, the reward is for victory over the things of the world. The wording of Revelation 2:10 is be thou faithful unto death, and I will give thee a crown of life. The words being unto death and not in death seem to state that one need to be put to death in order to win this crown.\n2. This company of ransomed ones is said to wash their robes. These are they which came out of great tribulation, and have washed their robes, and made them white in the blood of the Lamb `[animal_Lamb_Jhn_1]` [v_Rev_7_14] (Revelation 7:14). Modern Bible translations and the vast majority of commentators change this verse to eliminate the required washing by the individual. This is done in an attempt to bring the word of God into conformity with their limited understanding. Since a church-age saint is given the pure and spotless [v_2Co_5_21] righteousness of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Christ (2 Corinthians 5:21), these shallow teachers suppose that such must be the case in every period of time. Such men will condemn the Bible because it disagrees with their theology. This passes for scholarship in these apostate times. The fact of the matter is that the tribulation saints must keep themselves [v_Rev_13_16] without spot (Revelation 13:16, James 1:27), and this cleanness will [v_Rev_13_15] result in their execution (Revelation 13:15). Thus, the washing of the robes indicates a measure of reward for the tribulation saints, as they have earned for themselves an honor which was freely given to the church.\n2. We may have all material possession and provision, but without God\u2019s words there is neither true life nor real living.\n2. But speak thou the things which become sound doctrine: That the aged men be sober, grave, temperate, sound in faith, in charity, in patience (vv. 1\u20132). The punctuation will not allow us to separate these two verses. Sound doctrine is not separate from the way a man lives. A man\u2019s life is to be doctrinally sound. There is nothing here about knowing where to put the seven churches in relation to the Lord\u2019s coming. There is not a thought here as to setting forth the mystery doctrines in Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 parables. The scripture says if we are going to teach sound doctrine, we will be showing saved men how to be right in their mind, right in their emotions, right in governing their spirit, living a life of faith and of love and of longsuffering. Teaching men to do what is right in the sight of God is sound doctrine! Suppose you were a child growing in this society. When you were seven years old, your dad packed up and left. Your mother struggled to get by; you had a tough time; and you ended up in a gang or in a drug crowd. Suppose at the age of twenty, you tracked down your father and found him. And he said, \u201cListen, I\u2019m a great dad. I believe in the inspiration of scripture. I believe in the virgin birth and the blood atonement. I believe salvation is by grace.\u201d Seriously?! Would you applaud him because his doctrine was correct, or would you despise him because with all that head knowledge he lacked sound doctrine? The answer is obvious. Knowing some things about God and the Bible does not help anyone if the Lord Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Christ and His ways do not have influence over our ways. With regard to sound doctrine, Titus 2 continues, The aged women likewise, that they be in behaviour as becometh holiness (\n2. He continually revises, amends, and rewrites the text of the Authorized Version, then bases his Bible teaching on words not found in the Bible.\n2. The return in view here is the Son of Man (not the Savior) in glory (not the rapture) with his angels (not for His church).\n2. Who defines this self-denial? If I own a home and have more than one change of clothes have I denied myself? If I have money in my pocket have I denied myself?",
